I think Jon was thinking more in terms of authoring tools that of browsers, although both options are possible. 
The issue with authoring tools is that pages the might be authored off-line and the "automaric title extraction" is not possible, otherwise, it could be nice addition as it can help validating the link going out of a page at authoring time. 
It is an easy rule for people to remember when people are hand coding the TITLE attribute of an ANCHOR. 
There is no ambiguty on what to put in the TITLE attribute. 
Just put the TITLE in the HEADER block of the referenced document. 
This would be easy to explain in the guidelines. 
ALT text could be a short description of the image (icon, logo, picture) or the purpose of the image (chart, graph, map). 
LONGDESC would be an interpretation of the image. 
